==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}}, from {{etyl|fro|en}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|lang=la|fervens}}, present participle of {{term|lang=la|fervere||to boil, ferment, glow, rage}}.

===Adjective===
{{en-adj}}

# [[exhibit|Exhibit]]ing particular [[enthusiasm]], [[zeal]], [[conviction]], [[persistence]], or [[belief]].
#* '''1819''', [[w:Mary Wollstonecraft Shelley|Mary Wollstonecraft Shelley]], ''Mathilda'', ch. 3:
#*: As I returned my '''fervent''' hopes were dashed by so many fears.
# Having or showing [[emotion]]al [[warmth]], [[fervor]], or [[passion]].
#* '''1876''', [[w:Wilkie Collins|Wilkie Collins]], "Mr. Captain and the Nymph," in ''Little Novels'',
#*: Never again would those fresh lips touch his lips with their '''fervent''' kiss!
# [[glowing|Glowing]], [[burning]], very [[hot]].
#* '''1611''', [[w:King James Version of the Bible|King James Version of the Bible]], [[w:Second Epistle of Peter|Second Epistle of Peter]], [[s:Bible (King James)/2 Peter#Chapter 3|3:10]]:
#*: But the day of the Lord will come as a thief in the night; in the which the heavens shall pass away with a great noise, and the elements shall melt with '''fervent''' heat, the earth also and the works that are therein shall be burned up.

